article.headline: Hoosiers held to 19 percent shooting in 2nd half
article.linkText: No. 22 Michigan State takes control of Indiana
article.story:
EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Reserve Rene Haynes scored 11 points
and Michigan State (No. 22 ESPN/USA Today, No. 23 AP) used defense to make the difference in a
59-41 victory over Indiana on Friday night in the Big Ten opener
for both teams.

It was the sixth straight win for the Spartans (10-1), who
snapped a six-game losing streak in conference openers.

Kelli Roehrig and Liz Shimek each had nine points while Julie
Pagel and Kristin Haynie each added eight in coach Joanne P.
McCallie's 100th game at Michigan State.

The Spartans -- No. 1 in the league in points allowed and
opponents' field goal percentage -- held the Hoosiers (7-5) to 33
percent shooting from the field, including 19 percent in the second
half. Michigan State has allowed an average of 46.5 points and 32
percent shooting in its last six games.

Jenny DeMuth had 20 points for Indiana, which had just four
field goals in the second half, missed 12 of 22 free throws and
committed 22 turnovers.

The Spartans led 20-17 when Haynes led a 9-0 flurry with seven
quick points to give the team a 33-24 halftime lead.

Michigan State scored the first seven points of the second half
and held Indiana scoreless for the first 6:04. Another 13-0 run
midway through the half put the game away.
